Sitting in an exit seat?
Passenger Selection Criteria for Exit Seating
Federal Aviation Regulations require that passengers seated in an exit seat are able to perform the
Emergency Exit Seat Duties and meet all Selection Criteria as listed below. After reviewing this safety
information card, please identify yourself to a crewmember for reseating if you:
1. Cannot meet the selection criteria;
2. Have a condition, which is not apparent, that would prevent you from performing the duties listed;
3. May suffer bodily harm as a result of performing one or more of the duties listed;
4. Do not wish to perform the exit duties in the event of an emergency.
Emergency Exit Seat Duties
In the event of an emergency in which a crewmember is not available to assist, you may be called upon to
perform the following duties:
1. Locate the emergency exit;
2. Recognize the emergency exit opening mechanism;
3. Comprehend the instructions for operating the emergency exit;
4. Operate the emergency exit;
5. Assess whether opening the emergency exit will increase the hazards to which passengers may be exposed;
6. Follow oral directions (in English) and hand signals given by a, crewmember;
7. Remove the window exit, slide it lengthwise out of the opening and push it away from the exit path outside;
8. Assess the condition of the escape slide, activate the slide, and stabilize the slide after deployment to assist
others in getting off the slide;
9. Pass quickly through the emergency exit;
10. Assess, select, and follow a safe path away from the emergency exit.
Selection Criteria
You may not sit in an exit seat if you are unable to perform the Emergençy Exit Seat Duties as
described above because:
1. You lack sufficient mobility, strength, or dexterity in both arms and hands, and both legs:
(i) To reach upward, sideways, and downward to the location of emergency exits and exit-slide operating mechanisms;
(ii) To grasp and push, pull, turn, or otherwise manipulate those mechanisms;
(iii) To push, shove, pull, or otherwise open emergency exits;
(iv) To lift out, hold, deposit on nearby seats, or maneuver over the seat backs to the next row objects the size
and weight of the overwing exit doors;
(v) To remove obstructions similar in size and weight to overwing exit doors;
(vi) To reach the emergency exit quickly;
(vii) To maintain balance while removing obstructions;
(viii) To exit quickly;
(ix) To stabilize an exit slide after deployment; or
(x) To assist others in getting off an escape slide.
2. You are less than 15 years of age or lack the capacity to perform one or more of the applicable functions
without the assistance of an adult companion, parent, or other relative;
3. You lack the ability to read and understand printed or graphic instructions or the ability to understand oral (in
English) crew commands;
4. You lack the visual capacity to perform the duties without the assistance of visual aids beyond contact lenses
or eyeglasses;
5. You lack sufficient aural capacity to hear and understand instructions shouted by flight attendants, without
the assistance beyond a hearing aid;
6. You lack the ability to impart information orally to other passengers;
7. You have:
(1) A condition or responsibility, such as caring for a small child, that might prevent you from performing one or
more of the duties;
(ii) A condition that might cause you harm if you perform one or more of any of the duties. 2008.055.854
